# Context filter for the AI service image (TD81(a); see apps/ai-service/Dockerfile).
#
# NOTE THE SCOPE: docker reads the .dockerignore at the ROOT OF THE BUILD CONTEXT,
# and this image's context is apps/ai-service (NOT the repo root, unlike
# apps/api/Dockerfile). So the repo-root .dockerignore does NOT apply to this
# build — every exclusion this image needs has to be stated here.
#
# The Dockerfile COPYs `app/` and `scripts/` explicitly rather than `COPY . .`, so
# these entries are defence in depth rather than the only guard — but they also
# keep the context itself small (nothing is uploaded to the daemon/BuildKit that
# is not needed), which is the point of scoping the context this tightly.

# Never ship an env file into an image. config.py anchors its env_file to
# apps/ai-service/.env (AI-ENV-1), so a copied .env would be LOADED at boot —
# baking whatever a developer's laptop happens to hold into a pushed layer, where
# `docker history` makes it readable to anyone who can pull. .env.staging.example
# is a placeholder-only template and still has no business in a runtime image.
.env
.env.*

# Local virtualenv — a host-built venv is the wrong platform/interpreter anyway,
# and it is by far the largest thing in this directory.
.venv
venv

# Python + tooling caches (stale bytecode compiled against another interpreter).
**/__pycache__
**/*.py[cod]
.pytest_cache
.ruff_cache
.mypy_cache
.coverage
htmlcov

# The test suite and its dev-only dependencies are a CI gate
# (.github/workflows/ci.yml → ruff + pytest), not a runtime artifact.
tests
requirements-dev.txt

# Docs / build metadata: pyproject.toml here configures pytest + ruff only (the
# service is run with uvicorn, never installed as a package), so nothing at
# runtime reads any of these.
README.md
pyproject.toml
Dockerfile
.dockerignore
